SIMPLE: polish
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Polish
<hw>Pol"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Pole</er> a
Polander.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Poland or its
inhabitants.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>The language of the
Poles.</def></def2>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Polish
<hw>Pol"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Polished</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Polishing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>polir</ets>,
L. <ets>polire</ets>. Cf. <er>Polite</er>, <er>-ish</er>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make smooth and glossy, usually by friction; to
burnish; to overspread with luster; <as>as, to <ex>polish</ex> glass,
marble, metals, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to refine; to wear off the rudeness,
coarseness, or rusticity of; to make elegant and polite; <as>as, to
<ex>polish</ex> life or manners</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To polish off</b></col>, <cd>to finish completely, as an
adversary.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>W. H.
Russell.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Polish
<hw>Pol"ish</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become smooth, as from
friction; to receive a gloss; to take a smooth and glossy surface;
<as>as, steel <ex>polishes</ex> well</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Polish
<hw>Pol"ish</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A smooth, glossy
surface, usually produced by friction; a gloss or luster.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Another prism of clearer glass and better <qex>polish</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything used to produce a gloss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Fig.: Refinement; elegance of manners.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This Roman <qex>polish</qex> and this smooth behavior.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polishable</ent>⟦br⟧
